aas:description.aas:langString: data model for vehicle diagnostic data suitable for mass data transfer
list of diagnostic sessions, e.g. from a list of vehicles/fleet

One diagnostic session of one vehicle: Depending on the diagnostic software used in either workshops or over-the-air diagnostics one session can be defined differently: - Workshop diagnostic: Normally for each command to the diagnostic tester is a session diagnostic file created that is later send to the OEM backend system. Examples for one command: Read-out all ECUs with its DTCs or do a Software upgrade of one ECU - Over-the-air: E.g. one diagnostic snapshot is taken after ignition-on
In addition a list of environment conditions can be placed as well as a list of AdditionalInfos.
Both lists are on DiagnosticDataSession level because they can be valid for the whole vehicle(e.g. environment temperature) or only for a specific ECU (e.g. wheel speed sensor at ABS ECU)
date-timestamp for this session according ISO 8601 when this session was created. Depending on OEM this attribute reflects the start or end date of one diag session
Format OEM-specific: A unique session identifier within one OEM.
A unique quality task identifier where these list of session data belongs to. Optional to ensure that also Diagnostic Data without assigned qTask can be exchanged.
country code in ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 codes where this session took place
current mileage counter of the car during the diagnostic session
all attributes to clearly identify the vehicle during this diagnostic session
OEM-specific hashed VIN; link to car data over pseydomized/hashed VIN or Catena-X unique digital twin identifier
A fully anonymous Catena-X identifier that is registered in C-X Digital twin registry. This proprty be used for vehicles, parts, workshops, ..... Optional: Not always available
Software category of this car during the session - only available for OEMs that have a software category on vehicle level.
Software version of this car during the session - only available for OEMs that have a software category on vehicle level.
all attributes to clearly identify this workshop
OEM internal workshop ID
A fully anonymous Catena-X identifier that is registered in C-X Digital twin registry. This proprty be used for vehicles, parts, workshops, ..... Optional: Not always available

A single ECU that is present/has a DTC set in the diagnostic session
A fully anonymous Catena-X identifier that is registered in C-X Digital twin registry. This proprty be used for vehicles, parts, workshops, ..... Optional: Not always available

list of diagnostic trouble codes

diagnostic trouble codes or short DTCs are used inside ECUs to monitor failures. They were introduced for measuring vehicle emissions. Major DTCs for emissions are standardized by ISO standard ISO 15031-6:2015 - so called OBD2 standard. Over time DTCs were also introduced in other ECUs also besides engine and emission control. Many DTCs are vehicle manufacturer specific.
serial number of ECU
Hex value of this DTC

combined string of DTC name plus the so called DTC sub type or DTC failure byte. Both string values are concatenated using a "-" as separator. DTC name is: B|C|P|U + 4 hex chars DTC failure byte: 2 hex chars
In some rare cases this could be just a hex string
description of DTC and failure byte. Both description strings are concatenated using a "-" as separator
